the late nineteenth to the mid-twentieth centuries. In the first part of the book, he looks at how the attempts of heritage society members and political leaders to define the Alamo as a place have reflected struggles within Texas society over the place and status of Anglos and Mexicans. In the second part, he explores how Alamo movies and the transformation of Davy Crockett into an Alamo hero/martyr have advanced deeply racialized, ambiguous, and even invented understandings of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMexican AmericanszTexasxSocial conditions. 0aPopular culturezTexas. 0aSymbolismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWhiteszTexasxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796478/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK